</p>

<h2>What CSS Minification Actually Does</h2>

<p>
  A CSS minifier performs several lossless transformations — the output is functionally identical to the input, just smaller:
</p>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Removes whitespace</strong> — spaces, tabs, and newlines between declarations</li>
  <li><strong>Strips comments</strong> — all <code>/* */</code> blocks removed</li>
  <li><strong>Shortens values</strong> — <code>#ffffff</code> → <code>#fff</code>, <code>0px</code> → <code>0</code>, <code>font-weight: bold</code> → <code>font-weight:700</code></li>
  <li><strong>Merges shorthand</strong> — <code>margin: 10px 10px 10px 10px</code> → <code>margin:10px</code></li>
  <li><strong>Removes overridden properties</strong> — duplicate declarations in the same rule are deduplicated</li>
  <li><strong>Normalizes selectors</strong> — removes redundant universal selectors and simplifies combinators</li>
</ul>

<pre><code>{codeBeforeAfter}</code></pre>

<p>
  The whitespace alone accounts for most of the savings. For a real-world stylesheet with extensive comments and multi-line formatting, 40–60% reduction is typical.
</p>

<h2>Performance Impact: Why This Matters</h2>

<p>
  CSS is render-blocking. Before the browser can display anything, it must download, parse, and apply all stylesheets in the <code>&lt;head&gt;</code>. Smaller CSS means:
</p>

<ul>
  <li>Faster download on slow connections (100KB → 50KB saves ~500ms on 3G)</li>
  <li>Less parse time, directly improving Time to First Contentful Paint (FCP)</li>
  <li>Better Largest Contentful Paint (LCP) and overall Core Web Vitals scores</li>
  <li>Reduced bandwidth costs, especially relevant for high-traffic sites</li>
</ul>

<p>
  For context, Google's PageSpeed Insights and Lighthouse both flag unminified CSS as an opportunity. It's a checkbox item that eliminates a performance warning with minimal effort.
</p>

