<h2>cssnano: The PostCSS-Based Standard</h2>

<p>
  For project integration, <strong>cssnano</strong> is the most widely used CSS minifier in the Node.js ecosystem. It runs as a PostCSS plugin and has sensible defaults that are safe for production:
</p>

<pre><code>{codeCssnano}</code></pre>

<p>
  cssnano's default preset applies conservative optimizations. For maximum compression, the <code>advanced</code> preset applies more aggressive transforms like deduplicating <code>@keyframes</code> and reducing <code>calc()</code> expressions — but test thoroughly before using <code>advanced</code> in production.
</p>

<h2>clean-css: Fast, Configurable CLI</h2>

<p>
  <strong>clean-css</strong> is a battle-tested minifier with an easy-to-use CLI. It's particularly useful for build scripts that concatenate and minify multiple CSS files:
</p>

<pre><code>{codeCleanCss}</code></pre>

<p>
  clean-css supports compatibility targets (like Browserslist) so it knows which optimizations are safe for your target browsers. It also generates source maps, which are essential for debugging minified CSS in production.
</p>

